segments.text: to be in Austin chatting with Speaker Bill Clayton about his reminiscences and recollections of being a student at Texas A&M.
As we began, first question, why did you go to A&M?
Well, I have a good friend at Spring Lake, Texas,
I was drafted.
Right immediately after building the camp, I was sent overseas and was shot for the first big Israel kill.
And I wanted to do something about it.
And I was too young to be...
I went to volunteer.
I was 17 years old.
And they wouldn't let me in.
I believe I was 17.
I might have been 16.
And so then I looked around.
to see how else I might be able to accomplish that.
And wanting to get into college, I knew that I had to have some more credits for wanting my little high school offer.
It was a period of war when there wasn't any good teachers left, men teachers.
A lot of the subject matters, science and mathematics, advanced math, was just not there.
I enrolled in Texas Tech, or was trying to enroll in Texas Tech.
I was married about a week before they told me I just wasn't qualified to have any of these other subjects.
So I decided then to find me a place where I could go and pick up those last senior subjects that I needed, and it was Allen Academy in Bryan, Texas.
Well, I got quite an attachment to A&M while I was at Allen Academy.
Now, what year was that?
This was in 1946.
So it was just natural that I moved from there to A&M.
And certainly I've never regretted it.
So you enrolled as a freshman in the fall of?
And you were at Allen in 45, 46?
Right.
High school was Spring Lake?
Uh-huh.
came to enroll as a freshman in the fall of 46.
How did you get there?
Describe that trip.
Well, I believe on that first occasion my parents brought me back.
But it was a long way to West Texas.
And, you know, of course in them days it was all Corps, all military.

Once you didn't get a chance to go home except just one or two times during the semester, I believe Easter maybe, and then in the fall you got to go to Thanksgiving and Christmas, and that was about it.
And our mode of transportation in them days was hitchhiking.
Describe Aggie hitchhiking.
Well, we had old Highway 6, which is right out in front of the campus, in front of the demonstration building.
Aggies would line up there.
and they would take their turn, one behind the other as they had lined up, and thumbing a ride.
And you know, with the uniforms on in that day and time, and the war just about to come to a close, everybody stopped for a uniform to pick them up and carry them where they were going.
And so I remember standing in that line several times.
Do you remember any
Important stories about hitchhiking, good or bad?
Interesting experiences?
Yes, I do.
One summer school, on the 4th of July, my roommate and I decided to see how far we could hitchhike on the weekend and get back to classes.
We took off and we got to Chicago.
And it was an interesting deal.
In Texarkana, we caught a truck going to St. Louis.
It was raining.
I mean, we were out there just getting drenched.
And this truck stopped and picked us up.
St. Louis on the edge of Chicago.
I forgot now who we caught, but it was one ride.
And of course, the interesting thing was,
when we stayed one night there in Chicago.
And on the way back, we caught a guy with, at that time, the latest model Buick.
You know, they kind of would make cars for a while there.
And this guy was, he was an amazing guy.
He was talking about owning
an aircraft.
We didn't know where it was blowing or, you know, whether it was a real thing or what.
And, of course, the amazing thing was, too, that as we just began to realize as we were driving along, he was about half drunk.
And reaching on the cedar once in a while to fill out the bottle and, you know, it kind of put the fear in you a little bit.
He had passed the bottle around and we'd partake because we'd
We're so dang scared we didn't know what not to do.
But he kept telling us a story about he had a mansion in St. Louis with 25 rooms and all kinds of things like that.
Well, lo and behold, he took us and showed us one in St. Louis.
So he was real.
And so we spent a major portion of the night in St. Louis.
Did he identify his profession?
You know, he may have, I have forgotten.
Anyway, we got back on the road, got back to College Station Monday morning, and missed an 8 o'clock class and made it 9 o'clock.
And that was quite a... Y'all left?
We left on, I believe it was Friday about noon.
Do you remember any negative hitchhiking?
From what experience?
And I attacked a lot, but there's only one experience that I remember was negative.
And the guy that lived in Olsen, Texas, which is about six miles from Spring Lake, in fact, I believe it was at that time, and we were hitching back home, and we got a ride somewhere
right like where it was it was probably uh before you it was before we got that and it was a sharp ride and we got him and this guy got talking about his experience the night before with a young boy

and he just kept on and said you know what he just went into details and we made him pull over and stop and we got out but that's the only experience i ever had that even could have turned to that all right now hitchhiking from con station to spring lake what was the normal route uh routes uh well we went on highway six uh that time c6 before uh highway uh interstate 20
Highway 6 now cuts off, I think, at Cisco or Eastland or somewhere there.
But at that time, it went on through Abilene.
And then from Abilene, I think we took 84.
Describe the campus physically.
What buildings were where when you were a freshman?
Very little on the west campus, the dairy.
As far as classrooms on the west campus, there wasn't any.
There was a lot of buildings there then that are not there now, like Hyatt Hall and Walden and some of those.
There was about 6,000 of us in the Corps.
We were in the new area, we called it at that time, which really wasn't too old.
And you know, it was an experience that I don't think anybody can forget, because our freshman class was probably the worst hazed class that came down the pike in a long time.
And this was just before it closed down.
They left right on the air base.
They and Emma took it over.
Some of us were out there for classes.
And then some were on campus.
But man, the hazing was something just unbelievable.
Describe that.
Well, it would be nothing at all to be walking to the classroom and just buckled down because your knees get out because the morning before or the night before you had to do sternum and knee bends.
Or to stand on your tiptoes and grab butterflies with razor blades under your heels.
I mean, that kind of stuff.
And the paddle was a well-known weapon for the upper draftsmen at that time.
If a paddle was used, when and how many licks?
Usually it was, I'm trying to think, it seemed like it was three after a warm-up.
But I have gone to the shower, and I've gone to the shower many times to soak my shorts on because I've got a mistake.
Now, normally when you were paddled, you had on your trousers or just your shorts?
Usually just my shorts.
And did you have to do anything bad to get that paddling?
You know, I don't remember, but I can't recall what we would think was bad to get it.
You were living on the campus or at Bryan Field?
I lived on the Bryan Field.
Okay.
Describe that.
Because that's kind of special.

Well, at that time, as the Air Force moved out, and then just moved in, and we were in the same dormitories, you know, with 15, 20, I guess 12, 15 rows of beds on each side, and the head down at the end of one of the barracks.
And about how many fish were out there?
I think the whole freshman class was out there.
Any sophomores?
Yeah, we had our classmen out there.
That's where we got our A's.
Okay.
We had just the regular officers that, you know, you have in a company or a battalion, sophomores, juniors, and seniors.
And you were out there the whole year?
Yeah.
The whole academic year.
How often did y'all come into the campus?
We came in quite a few times for
A lot of military drills and things like that.
Football games?
Yeah.
Oh, yeah.
Y'all practice?
Yes.
And did the faculty live out there?
I don't know.
But you had all your classes out there.
Yes.
Let's see.
You didn't have a fish old lady then, since you didn't have a roommate.
Well, we were all roommates.
That's it?
Yeah.
So y'all didn't use that term, fish old lady?
Well, we used the term because it was double bunk.
Oh, okay.
And the one that doubled with you was your old lady.
Who were some special friends that you made then that you recall now?
Oh, gosh.
Really, I can't remember that far back.
There's some that I...
and they're all dead.
Bell trot, necktie, just a few of them.
Please describe the chow hall routine, ritual.
Well, it wasn't a ritual.
It was... working in the chow hall was probably the best job on campus.
You could get all the cooks you wanted.
Did you work in the chow hall?
I worked in the mess hall some.
And I also worked in the mess hall when we went to my campus.
But, you know, the manner in which you were seated, the upperclassmen would serve first.
line first and they got everything passed to them before anybody else started then.
Then I've seen we've had of course the bread fights.
Describe the bread fight.
Well it's basically what we do is somebody would
on one of the tables, two or three tables over, try to take a roll on an upperclassman that was turned the other direction.
And that usually started that table throwing back into that table.
And the first thing you know, it looked like a mirage coming across.
And you threw bread and what else?
Well, occasionally we got a little sloppy and throw some other stuff, but it was mainly bread.
Any, describe a typical day, class day.
When did it begin and what happened when?
Go through the whole day for me.
Well, we were always, I forget what time we had to be up, but we were always in formation doing military things before we went to class.
And if I'm correct, I believe our classes, some of them started at 7, some of them started at 8.
And they lasted all through the day, just like we do now.
And at that time, I believe, I don't guess we had any weekend classes.
I was thinking maybe we did, but I don't believe we did.
But you did have Saturday classes.
Yes.
Did you all march to class?
Yes.
When there was a group going to a certain class, like a big chemistry lab or something like that, yes.
Did you all fall in for lunch?
Yes.
And supper.
What about late in the afternoon?
What did you all do late afternoon?
Intramurals and then study.
Then at night?
Yeah, the study periods at night.
And what time lights out?
Ten o'clock.
Did anybody ever try to get up after hours and move around?
They didn't try it, they didn't.
What'd they do?
Oh, I know several cases.
A couple of my buddies and I, we'd slip out and go over to the Little Brazos and go swimming, things like that.
We kind of never did veer towards town because we thought we might get caught.
Occasionally we'd go across the bridge
and pick up some goodies and come home.
Now what was over across the bridge?
It was a wet area of that particular region at that time.
Two or three liquor stores was about the first place you could buy liquor.
Were any of them famous or infamous by name?
Well we just called it the bridge.
It was two or three of them.
Of course you know
Before you got the bridge, if you was going down on the back roads, one of the famous beer halls would come Uncle Ed's.
Now, where was Uncle Ed's?
I don't know the highway number, but it's like you were going to Dimebox, I guess, Welbert Road.
You're talking about going south from the main campus?
Yeah, from the main campus.
Was Uncle Ed's and Hard Liquor's the same place?
I've heard of them both.
I don't think it was.
It could have been.
It could have been Ed Hartnaker.
It might have been the name.
But you're right.
I've heard of both of them.
Let's see.
Your outfit.
D. Field, RTOB.
What was special about it, about that outfit?
Well, I thought we had one of the finer CEOs, a guy by the name of Harty, out of Houston.
And we just had a group of people that kind of gelled together.
The camaraderie was good.
Anybody got in their way, we'd fight for each other.
You stayed with that outfit all through?
Stayed with it till...
I don't know how to say this.
It changed designations from right in about that time.
It had to be changed to old.
But no, I didn't...
take a contract.
So last year and a half, I was not ready.
But you're in the Corps then for two years.
Let's see.
Food nicknames.
Cush or dessert.
Thank you.
Lord have mercy.
Meat.
Butter.
milk, tea?
Well, we had some pretty god awful nights.
That's all I can remember.
They weren't worth repeating in public.
How did you, how did you dress for class?
In a horse.
And what conduct did you think was expected of you in class?
I hadn't even thought about that.
You were there to listen and learn.
Did you go to sleep?
Occasionally you did, because upperclassmen had to do a darn lot of stuff, and hazing is so bad that you didn't get a whole lot of sleep.
Frank, you then, as a sophomore, you're on the main campus?
Right.
Describe how life was different then.
Not a whole lot different, because the freshman class was still out at the air base.
a handful of freshmen on campus.
Our outfit, by the way, happened to have a couple of them.
And, uh, let me go back to freshman year first.
Oh, please do.
Please do.
Uh, Gib Gilchrist was president of Bayland at that time.
And, of course, he was very high on trying to stop Beijing.
And, uh, when I was
I looked at the hippies of the 60s and their rebellion and how they demonstrated and all this kind of stuff, you know, I think, man, I'm never going to part with anything like that.
But I do remember when we were freshmen, we marched on Gilchrist's house and hung him an ethargy on the tree.
And so I guess you look back, you express yourself in a lot of ways, but I mean the whole core of us.
What happened when you all got to his house?
All I remember is we hung him and added tea.
But I don't know.
I don't know what happened there.
I'm really not certain.
Well, what came of that protest?
Did anything change?
I don't think so.
Yeah, that was a, yeah, I remember that .
All right, dining hall ritual then, you lived in the new core area, Sevesa or Duncan?
We lived, we were at Duncan.
Duncan.
Describe the dining hall ritual in Duncan.
Wasn't much different.
It was about the same as we had out at the base.
All right, so you're in the, you're eating in Duncan then your sophomore year.
And then as a DNC, did you continue to live on campus your junior, senior year?
Oh, yes.
Absolutely.
In fact, I lived in the new area.
OK.
But you wore a uniform.
Yeah.
OK. How was life then as a sophomore?
What privileges did you enjoy as a sophomore?
Well, we really didn't enjoy it as much as you would have if you had a crew of freshmen in your outfit.
It wasn't as bitter as it was, the hazing wasn't as, at some point, as it was when he was fresh.
And you're talking about a while ago, getting out after the lights were out and everything.
Many, many a night, I'd suggest probably every other night at least, maybe more often, we'd always get up and do drown outs.
Describe a drowned out.

Well, a drowned out is where you go to an upperclassman's room while they're asleep at night and dump a bucket of water or whatever else you might have accumulated on them and run like heck, hope they don't catch you.
And then what kind of retribution was there normally?
Oh, if you got caught, it was Katie Boy the Dover.
Because you got retribution that didn't last just one day.
It usually lasted longer than that.
Now, did you almost always drown out someone in a higher academic class than you?
Yeah, in a higher class where they, you know, like this is.
Describe for me some samples of Good Bull of the drown outs, pranks, jokes.
Well, I can remember one where we put a five gallon bucket in there.
And all the freshmen come by here and they didn't tell you it was bull.
We used that as a draft out for one of our senior officers one night that everybody just couldn't get along with.
I mean, there was a lot of fun things like that.
Did he get the message?
He got the message.
Any others you can?
Well, another prank that we had pulled,
to fill a condom up with water and slip it in the bed with them.
And sometimes, for warning, they'd tumble enough to break out and the water would go everywhere.
Ever any fireworks?
I don't remember.
What were the
unwritten rules of student behavior and pranks and jokes, what were the things that y'all just wouldn't do?
I don't know what much we didn't do.
Did anybody ever have a woman in their room at night?
Yes.
Describe your room.
in the core area?
My freshman year was hot water.
Let's do both.
Well, freshman year, of course, like I indicated, we used a barracks farm, double bunks on each side of the barracks.
I'd say there were probably 10 barracks on each row, probably about 20 students in a barracks.
And then we were trained,
one place for everybody.
On the campus, when we were in the dorms, in the core dorms, you'd have two or sometimes it'd be three children.
But it was an enclosure.
It didn't have a bathroom.
It wasn't fancy like the dorms are now.
I've been in some recently and they're just pretty nice.
It was just a concrete floor.
No elevators.
Always tires.
I can remember one occasion in our sophomore year.
Somebody had gone across the river.
It was in the afternoon.
And there was four or five of us in the dorm with a doughy shelf.
And had it locked.
And we were having a good time.
And, uh, we heard a knock on the door.
And it was Colonel Borger.
They're coming.
We didn't know it.
I hollered, the ship will slide under us.
And somebody opened the door, and when he walked in, let me tell you, that sobered the crowd up real quick.
Let's digress on him.
Describe Colonel, then Colonel Boehner.
He was just a tough old Army guy that he wanted you to go by the rule, and that was it.
No variation.
probably about, I'm just trying to visualize my mind, the size of the man he was.
He wasn't that tall, but he was a well-built, pretty broad fellow.
Did you all respect him?
Well, you did in his presence.
Yeah, you know, in later years, too, you begin to realize he was A-OK. Back in this...
core dorm room.
What was in that room?
A bunk bed, and were they one on top of the other or were they separated?
No, in ours there was one on top of each other.
And what else was in there?
That was it.
No air conditioning, nothing like that, and the little thin mattress pads and the hot summer and day in College Station.
You'd sweat that thing through in a night.
Where was the desk?
Yeah, there was a
It seemed like kind of a shelf-like thing for a desk, as best I recall.
There wasn't a whole lot of furniture, maybe a couple chairs.
Alright, and then normally when you came from Spring Lake to A&M, what did you bring as the year began?
About a whole lot.
Just, you know, personal effects as far as
a lot of closed things, you didn't because you'd all go over the issue of the wheelchair.
We didn't have, none of those kids had televisions and things like that to bring them days.
Did you even have a radio?
I think we might have had a small radio in our garden, but I'm not sure.
Who were some of the memorable teachers, advisors, counselors?
Well,
I have to say that probably, what's the old chemistry professor's name?
Herrington.
Dean Herrington.
He was probably one of the better teachers I ever had.
I flunked Chemistry 101 my first semester.
And I took it then the second semester under him.
And under him, I loved it.
I really was, I really thought he was a great teacher.
What made him a good teacher?
I really don't know, but I mean, he just made you, he had something or other that made you interested in what he was saying.
He had a way about it.
Did he have a nickname?
He had, I don't remember.
What about some of the other nicknames?
One of my professors,
